    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-22T21:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-22T21:30:00-05:00" n="1541"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1541">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">831.6363/1633: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Corrigan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caracas</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-22T22:00:00-04:30"
                            >April 22, 1944—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 23—2:44 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>435. Terms of new concession bids cited in Department’s 259 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >359</hi>], April 22, 1 p.m.,<note n="43" xml:id="d1541fn43">Not
                        printed.</note> have been discussed with British Minister<note n="44"
                        xml:id="d1541fn44">Donald St. Clair Gainer.</note> and are reported in air
                    mail despatch leaving by today’s pouch.<note n="45" xml:id="d1541fn45">Despatch
                        5799, April 22, 1944, not printed.</note> They involve an attempt to assure
                    refining of 10% of Venezuelan crude in Venezuela and shipment of remaining 90%
                    out of Caribbean area in crude form. Effect would be to by-pass Aruba and
                    Curaçao. Proposal affects Shell<note n="46" xml:id="d1541fn46">Royal Dutch Shell
                        Company.</note> interests much more vitally than it does our own.</p>
                <p>Head of largest American producing company here considers this an administrative
                    proposal which can be overcome and does not think it calls for diplomatic
                    protests at this time.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Corrigan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
